    title: "Tense Transformation & Question Formation",
    questionLimit: 40,
    timeLimit: 15,
    summary: "This chapter covers two key grammatical transformations: (1) converting past simple sentences to present perfect, and (2) forming questions from statements (both active and passive). These skills are fundamental to academic and professional English communication.",
    keyPoints: [
      "Past simple → Present perfect: Replace the past simple verb with 'have/has + past participle' — the subject determines whether 'have' or 'has' is used: singular third-person subjects use 'has'; all others use 'have'",
      "'Has' is used with singular third-person subjects: He, She, It, and singular nouns — e.g., 'The museum has put...', 'The hard work of all agents has impressed...'",
      "'Have' is used with plural subjects and I, You, We, They — e.g., 'The students have taken...', 'The catering crew have delayed...', 'Special forces personnel have located...'",
      "The present perfect signals a past action with present relevance, recently completed action, or accumulated experience — contrasted with past simple which refers to a completed action at a specific past time",
      "Past participle forms: regular verbs add '-ed' (checked → checked, applied → applied, asked → asked, prepared → prepared); irregular verbs change form (put → put, give → given, take → taken, go → gone, install → installed, discuss → discussed, arrest → arrested, locate → located, repulse → repulsed, impress → impressed)",
      "Question formation from statements: Move the auxiliary verb to the front — 'All flights have been cancelled' → 'Have all flights been cancelled?'; 'Beans and carrots CAN be cooked together' → 'Can beans and carrots be cooked together?'",
      "For past simple active statements, question formation requires inserting 'did' and returning the verb to base form: 'BOB PAINTED THE PICTURE' → 'Did Bob paint the picture?'; 'DANIEL WATCHED THE SUN GO DOWN' → 'Did Daniel watch the sun go down?'",
      "For past progressive active statements, question formation moves 'was/were' to the front: 'DANIEL WAS WATCHING THE BIRDS' → 'Was Daniel watching the birds?'",
      "For statements with modal verbs (will, can, must, should, etc.), question formation moves the modal to the front: 'COMPUTERS WILL REPLACE THE WORKERS' → 'Will computers replace the workers?'; 'DOGS MUST BE CARRIED ON THE ESCALATORS' → 'Must dogs be carried on the escalators?'",
      "For present simple statements, question formation uses 'do/does': 'BOYS LIKE TO PLAY SOCCER' → 'Do boys like to play soccer?'; 'CARS ARE MADE IN HONG KONG' → 'Are cars made in Hong Kong?' (passive already has auxiliary)",
      "For passive voice statements, the auxiliary 'to be' (is/are/was/were/being) already functions as question-forming auxiliary: 'DENNIS WAS ASKED A QUESTION BY KEVIN' → 'Was Dennis asked a question by Kevin?'; 'ALL FLIGHTS HAVE BEEN CANCELLED' → 'Have all flights been cancelled?'",
      "Key present perfect transformations from the GNS102 exam: 'arrested' → 'has arrested'; 'prepared' → 'have prepared'; 'checked' → 'have carefully checked'; 'delayed' → 'have delayed'; 'impressed' → 'has impressed'; 'put' → 'has put'; 'discussed' → 'have discussed'; 'taken' → 'have taken'; 'installed' → 'have installed'; 'located' → 'have located'; 'repulsed' → 'have repulsed'",
      "The present perfect is often used in academic writing to review literature: 'Previous scholars have examined the effects of...'; 'Researchers have found that...'; 'Studies have shown that...'"
    ],
